Game Design Document: Addendum I - Core Loop & UI

1. Aesthetic & Display Constraints
Vibe: Present-day California, sunny, highly detailed anime/Studio Ghibli style (rich watercolors, warm lighting, sunbeams). Cozy, low-stress, no gore.
Aspect Ratio & Layout: The game operates on a fixed 16:9 layout.
Ambient Pillarboxing: The pre-rendered isometric room art (e.g., 1072x1136) is centered vertically. The remaining horizontal screen space (left/right margins) is filled with a solid hex color defined in the Tiled map data (e.g., "AmbientColor": "#2A3B4C"). This dead space is explicitly used to house UI elements so the room art is never obscured.
Sprited Interactables: While the background is pre-rendered, items of interest (clues) are rendered as separate sprites layered on top, giving them a slight visual pop to guide the player's eye without needing glowing outlines.
2. The Single-Button Interaction System
To maximize mobile compatibility and ease of play, the cat uses a single contextual "Interact" input ( tap/click/Spacebar ) when overlapping a collision trigger.
Look (Objects): Pops up a high-res image and a short line of descriptive text.
Listen (NPCs): Pops up a dialogue box with a character portrait.
Consult (The Detective): Interacts with the "Doofus Detective" (the human owner) to open the Deduction Board and attempt to solve the case.
Note: The previously pitched "Smell Mode" shader and physical mid-level puzzles (pushing blocks, etc.) have been cut to keep development scope ruthlessly tight and focused on narrative deduction.
3. Clue System & "The Noise"
To prevent brute-forcing, the game utilizes a signal-to-noise ratio. The player will collect many keywords, including red herrings, inflating the mathematical permutations of the final puzzle.
Auto-Extraction: Clues are automatically added to the player's Notebook after an interaction.
Color-Coded Logic: Clues belong to strict categories, visually represented in both the dialogue text and the UI.
🟦 [WHO] (People, Suspects) - Blue
🟩 [WHAT] (Evidence, Objects, Items) - Green
🟧 [WHY] (Motives, Context) - Orange
🟪 [WHEN/WHERE] (Times, Locations) - Purple
Transformation: Dialogue text parses raw tags ({who:agatha}) into colored text. In the Notebook, this tag translates into a clear, objective statement (e.g., "Lady Agatha" or "Roderick insulted her").
4. UI & The Deduction Board (Tap-to-Fill)
The UI is designed to be completely tap/click driven. Drag-and-drop mechanics are explicitly avoided to ensure flawless mobile web performance.
The Notebook: Accessed via a pulsing icon in the ambient margin. Opens a clean, scrollable list of collected clues sorted into four colored tabs (Blue, Green, Orange, Purple).
The Deduction Board (Tester): Initiated by talking to the Detective. Displays a "Mad Libs" sentence with colored, empty slots.
Mechanic: The player taps an empty slot. A dropdown menu appears containing only the collected clues of that matching color. The player taps a clue to fill the slot.
The Obra Dinn Rule: The game never validates a single slot. Logic is only checked when the player hits a global "Submit" button.
5. Level Design Mechanics: The "Hide & Seek" Alpha Fade
To create a sense of exploration without a 3D camera, the Y-Sorting alpha-fade mechanic is repurposed as a core puzzle element.
By placing key objects physically behind tall foreground props (like desks or cabinets), the player cannot see the clue by default.
The player must naturally walk the cat behind the furniture. The furniture's alpha lerps to 0.4f (transparency), revealing the hidden object sprite underneath, rewarding spatial exploration.
6. The "Triangle Method" Deduction Formula
Cases are solved by connecting isolated facts. The game will rarely spell out the answer. Instead, it relies on A + B = C logic.
Example: The player finds a Torn Glove (A) hidden behind a cabinet. An NPC mentions they saw Chad wearing bandages (B). The player deduces that Chad was bitten by the stolen parrot (C).
Win State: Upon correct submission, the Detective realizes the truth based on the cat's actions (e.g., the cat knocks over the evidence, triggering the human's "Eureka" moment). Case closed.